passages.text: FIVE reported 2Q25 adj. EPS of \(\) 0.81\(the GS/consensus estimates of\) \ \(0.59 / \S 0.62\) . We note that sales increased \(+23.7\%\) to \(\) 1026.8\(mn and comparable store sales increased by +12.4\%\) . Our key takeaways from the quarter include: 1) 2Q comp beat, driven by stronger merchandising trends and operational efficiencies, 2) 3Q margins guided above expectations despite tariff headwinds, and 3) FIVE raised FY25 guidance, incorporating the 1H beat and continued acceleration in the 2H.

Management raised their FY25 guidance, which included net sales of \(\) 4.44-\ \(4.52bn (previously\) \ \(4.33 - \S 4.42bn\) ), SSS of \(5 - 7\%\) (previously \(3 - 5\%\) ), adjusted net income of \(\) 264- 286mn (previously\) \ \(235 - \S 261mn\) ), 150 store openings (unchanged), and adjusted diluted EPS of \(\) 4.76-\ \(5.16 (previously\) \ \(4.25 - \S 4.72\) ). Management also introduced 3Q guidance, which includes net sales of \(\) 950- 970mn (vs GS/consensus of\) \ \(940mn / \S 930mn\) ), SSS of \(5 - 7\%\) (vs GS/consensus of \(+3.0\% / + 2.3\%\) ), 50 store openings, adjusted net income of \(\) 7- \S 13mn (vs GS/consensus of\) \ \(0.3 / \S 0.9mn\) ), and adjusted diluted EPS of \(\) 0.12-\ \(0.24 (vs GS/consensus of\) \ \(0.01 / \S 0.02\) ).

We remain constructive on FIVE given the company's improved merchandising and marketing strategies that have proven successful in accelerating customer transactions. Specifically, the elasticity responses to their pricing adjustments this quarter prove their product is resonating with consumers. While FIVE raised their FY25 guidance, this could still be conservative given 4Q remains unchanged. We believe FIVE will likely see a continued acceleration to their top- line in the 2H given their strong momentum of interconnecting marketing, product newness, and in- store execution. We reiterate our Buy rating and increase our price target to \(\) 162\$

2Q comp beat, driven by stronger merchandising trends and operational efficiencies - FIVE delivered comparable sales growth of \(+12.4\%\) (vs. GS/consensus of \(\) 9.0\% / + 8.6\%\(), driven by transaction growth of \(+8.7\%\) and ticket growth of \(\) 3.4\%\(. They also delivered broad- based outperformance across 6 out of 8 worlds, with strength in loungewear, candy, beauty products, and travel necessities. Management called out four main initiatives that contributed to this higher growth: curating new, on- trend assortment, simplifying the shopping experience by implementing whole price points, improving in- stocks

and flow of product throughout their network of stores, and initiating marketing campaigns with viral creator content. Licensing continued to serve as a successful aspect of their assortment, as many customers resonated with the Stitch Surf Shop collaboration and the \(\) 7\$ licensed backpacks. These initiatives have proven to be successful, as they are driving customer acquisition through both new and repeat customers.

3Q margins guided above expectations despite tariff headwinds - Management is guiding towards a 3Q adjusted operating margin of \(1\%\) (compared to GS/consensus of \(- 0.2\% / - 0.2\%\) ), with 160 bps of deleverage in gross margin due to unmitigated tariff costs (previously guided towards \(- 225\) bps in 1Q), and 100 bps increase in SG&A due to higher incentive compensation and in- store labor. The improvement in margin is mainly driven by increased leverage on higher sales, as management is now guiding towards a \(+5 - 7\%\) comp for 3Q (vs. \(3 - 5\%\) previously). Specifically, the price adjustments management implemented in May and June will drive these higher sales, as they are pleased with the elasticity results and are seeing lower unit degradation from the consumer. These price adjustments drove a single digit growth in AUR this quarter, which management notes will likely remain consistent in future quarters, and will drive further sales growth to offset tariff costs.

FIVE raised FY25 guidance, incorporating the 1H beat and continued acceleration in the 2H - Given their better than expected performance in 2Q and their optimistic outlook on the 2H, management raised their FY25 guidance on both the top and bottom line. Management believes that their merchandising and supply chain efficiencies will continue to accelerate transaction growth in 3Q, as they are in a strong inventory position for Fall and Halloween. However, we note that this guidance remains unchanged for 4Q, as management is still guiding towards a +LSD comp range given the potential consumer uncertainty and competitive environment. We note that this guidance could be conservative given the acceleration in the business and management's plans for the holiday season. Specifically, management called out a strong in- stock inventory prepared for holiday, leaning into key holiday winners from last year, and chasing trending product such as lounge, decor, and stocking stuffers.

FIVE reported 2Q25 adj. EPS of \(0.81\) , above the GS/consensus estimate of \(\) 0.59/\(\) 0.62\(. Net sales increased\)+23.7\%\(y/y to\) \ \(1026.8m\) , above the GS/consensus estimates of \(\) 993.2m\(\)\mathfrak{g}992\(in, while comparable sales increased +12.4\% y/y, which compares to the GS/consensus estimates of +9.0\%/+8.6\%\). Adj. operating margin increased +91 b y/y to 5.4% y/s. GS/consensus of 4.0%/4.1%) as gross margin increased +69 b y/y to 33.4% while adj. SG&A as a % of sales decreased - 22 bps y/y to 28.1%.

We are increasing our FY25 adj. EPS estimate to \(\) 5.13\(from\) \ \(4.70\) to reflect accelerating top- line performance in the back half. We increase our FY26 and FY27 adj. EPS estimates to \(\) 5.70\(from\) \ \(5.25\) and \(\) 6.40\(from\) \ \(5.88\) respectively, to also account for these higher estimates and strong comp performance.
Exhibit 3:FIVE estimate change summary In \(\) millions,\(except per - share data
Source: Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

We are Buy- rated on FIVE. Our 12- month price target increases to \(162 (from\) 143) based on higher estimates, a market multiple of \(23.1x\) (vs. \(22.5x\) previously), and relative P/E multiples of downside/base/upside case of \(115\% /120\% /125\%\) (unchanged).

Downside risks include declining transactions as FIVE's core customer is pressured by inflationary headwinds and reduces discretionary spending; pressure on average ticket as customers gravitate toward lower- priced products; inventory availability issues and/or the lack of an attractive assortment; gross margin pressures from mix and shrink; and higher- than- expected SG&A pressure.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
